\begin{abstract}
Conventional educational tests don't really capture what a student can do, since everyone gets the same questions no matter their skill level. This paper describes a working prototype---a Multi-Agent MCQ-based Student Competency Analysis System---that grades student responses and studies learner competency across several cognitive domains through a fully LLM-driven pipeline. Drawing on the multi-agent competency-building framework of Outay \textit{et al.} \cite{outay2024}, we adapt their Assess--Predict--Oversee--Transit (APOT) model to a question-based assessment setting. Unlike Outay \textit{et al.}, who rely on deterministic KPI metrics inside an AR vocational training loop, we reinterpret their four APOT agents---LSAA, SOLMA, SOLPA, and SOLTA---as LLM-powered reasoning modules that work over natural language signals instead of numeric thresholds. The system is implemented in Django 4.2 with a CrewAI pipeline running three specialized agents on Google Gemini 2.5 Flash: an MCQ Evaluator Agent, a Difficulty Predictor Agent, and an Adaptive MCQ Overseer Agent. A dual-layer design keeps the UI snappy by using a synchronous rule-based fallback, while a background multi-agent pipeline handles the deeper, AI-driven competency analysis. Questions are generated on the fly by the LLM, so we don't have to rely on pre-calibrated Item Response Theory models or static item banks. A design-level walkthrough, along with implementation-level detail, shows that the system behaves consistently across three cognitive domains: Reasoning, Aptitude, and Verbal Ability.
\end{abstract}

