\section{Introduction}
% -------------------------------------------------------

Traditional educational tests follow a one-size-fits-all approach, giving every student the same set of questions regardless of their actual ability. The implicit assumption is that all learners progress at roughly the same pace, which just isn't true in practice. Strong students end up bored by questions that feel trivial, while weaker students get overwhelmed and disengage. Either way, the test fails to capture what learners at the extremes can actually do, and it gives instructors little useful information about individual strengths, weaknesses, or how a student is progressing \cite{weiss2004}.

On top of that, most existing assessment systems offer only generic feedback that doesn't really tell students where they're doing well or falling short. This lack of personalization gets in the way of accurate competency measurement, drags down engagement, and limits how efficiently students actually learn \cite{vygotsky1978}. Without some way to continuously adapt based on how a student is doing, the assessment stays rigid and can't reflect the fact that learning itself is dynamic \cite{mislevy2003}.

Computerized Adaptive Testing (CAT) tackles these problems by adjusting question difficulty in response to how the student is performing \cite{lord1980}. The catch is that most CAT systems lean on Item Response Theory (IRT), which needs large pre-calibrated item banks and carefully validated statistical parameters \cite{hambleton1985}. That's a hard sell for smaller institutions, and the question-selection logic can feel like a black box to educators. We looked at IRT early in our design and ruled it out for two practical reasons: (i)~we had no calibrated item bank of our own, and building one would mean running large pilot studies before the system could even be used; and (ii)~IRT's probabilistic machinery is difficult to explain to teachers who are expected to trust the system's decisions.

Recent progress with Large Language Models (LLMs) opens up another path: baking the adaptation logic directly into intelligent agents. LLM-powered agents can reason over correctness and response time together, applying natural language rules to make context-aware difficulty decisions that feed straight into competency analysis. The rules themselves live inside the agent's backstory as plain English, which is much easier for a non-ML educator to read and question than a set of IRT parameters.

Outay \textit{et al.} \cite{outay2024} introduced the APOT (Assess--Predict--Oversee--Transit) model, managed by a Multi-Agent System (MAS) for competency building. Their design includes the Learning Style Assessment Agent (LSAA), Stage of Learning Monitoring Agent (SOLMA), Stage of Learning Prediction Agent (SOLPA), and Stage of Learning Transition Agent (SOLTA). While their framework gives us a solid starting point, it was built for augmented reality (AR)-based vocational training and depends on deterministic KPI metrics computed from sensor streams. Our setting is very different: a student sits in front of a browser and picks an option from four. There are no KPIs to read off hardware, only correctness and response time. We therefore take the APOT model's cyclic stages and agent role separation and adapt them into a fully LLM-driven, question-based environment for analyzing student competency.

This paper proposes an Adaptive Multi-Agent Student Competency Analysis System with the following contributions:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item A three-agent CrewAI pipeline powered by Gemini 2.5 Flash that maps to the APOT agents (SOLMA, SOLPA, SOLTA), swapping out formula-driven scoring for LLM-native contextual reasoning to analyze student competency across cognitive domains.
    \item A dual-layer difficulty adaptation scheme that pairs a synchronous rule-based fallback with asynchronous multi-agent LLM analysis, plus LLM-driven dynamic question generation that removes the need for a static item bank.
    \item An interpretable, prompt-engineered adaptation mechanism that skips IRT pre-calibration entirely while keeping the system both responsive and explainable across three cognitive domains.
    \item A working implementation, with concrete tooling choices (Django, CrewAI, Gemini 2.5 Flash, MySQL) and specific code patterns that other practitioners can reuse or critique.
\end{enumerate}

