\section{Related Work}
% -------------------------------------------------------

\subsection{Multi-Agent Systems in Education}
Multi-Agent Systems (MAS) have drawn a lot of attention in educational technology \cite{wooldridge2009}. Outay \textit{et al.} \cite{outay2024} proposed the APOT model with four agents: the \textbf{LSAA} (Learning Style Assessment Agent), which evaluates a learner's modality preferences; the \textbf{SOLMA} (Stage of Learning Monitoring Agent), which tracks current performance; the \textbf{SOLPA} (Stage of Learning Prediction Agent), which predicts learner potential; and the \textbf{SOLTA} (Stage of Learning Transition Agent), which decides when a learner moves between competency stages. Together, these agents compute a Learning Index (LI) and Competency Index (CI) to track progress. That said, their framework targets vocational AR training, so it doesn't transfer cleanly to digital question-based assessment. Unlike Outay \textit{et al.} \cite{outay2024}, our system does not rely on deterministic KPI metrics derived from physical task execution; instead, each agent reasons in natural language over two observables (correctness, time taken), and the LSAA role is pushed into domain-aware question generation rather than a dedicated modality-profiling agent.

\subsection{Computerized Adaptive Testing}
CAT has been studied since the 1970s and is generally seen as a robust way to personalize assessment \cite{weiss2004}. Most CAT systems rely on IRT, where each question carries parameters like difficulty, discrimination, and guessing probability \cite{lord1980}. IRT-based CAT is statistically rigorous, but it needs large, carefully calibrated item banks that take a lot of time and money to build \cite{hambleton1985}. The probabilistic machinery also tends to be opaque to educators. Where Lord \cite{lord1980} and Hambleton and Swaminathan \cite{hambleton1985} build their selection rules on estimated item parameters, we drop the parameter estimation step entirely and let an LLM agent reason over observable signals (correctness and response time) using transparent natural language heuristics. The price we pay is non-determinism, which we discuss openly in Section~\ref{sec:limitations}.

\subsection{LLM-Augmented Assessment Frameworks}
Recent LLM advances have made it easier to bring these models into educational systems for feedback, tutoring, and content creation \cite{chen2023}. Frameworks like CrewAI and AutoGen \cite{liang2023} support LLM-augmented agent collaboration. We chose CrewAI over AutoGen for a specific reason: CrewAI's declarative role/goal/backstory model mapped very naturally onto the APOT agent definitions we were trying to reproduce, and its sequential \texttt{Process.sequential} mode let us chain three tasks with almost no boilerplate. AutoGen \cite{liang2023} is more flexible for open-ended multi-turn conversation between agents, but our pipeline is a straight three-step chain where each agent runs once per question, so we didn't need that flexibility.

Bloom's taxonomy \cite{bloom1956} informs our three-level difficulty scheme (Easy, Medium, Hard). Reinforcement learning \cite{sutton2018} and Bayesian student models \cite{conati2002} are possible alternatives, but both require significant training data that we don't have. Conati \textit{et al.} \cite{conati2002}, for instance, rely on Bayesian networks trained on logged tutoring interactions, which works well in long-running tutoring systems but fits poorly in our short, single-session assessment use case. Unlike earlier systems that limit LLMs to generating feedback, our setup hands the entire competency analysis pipeline---evaluation, difficulty prediction, and adaptation---to LLM agents.

