\subsection{Assessment Workflow}
The system runs a per-question adaptive loop across 20 questions per session. For each question, we capture the student's selected answer and how long they took. The MCQ Evaluator Agent checks whether the answer is correct; the Difficulty Predictor Agent classifies the difficulty of that question; and the Adaptive MCQ Overseer Agent pulls everything together and recommends the difficulty level for the next question. Three cognitive domains are supported: Reasoning, Aptitude (with aliases Quantitative Aptitude, Quant), and Verbal Ability (with aliases Verbal, English), and topic normalization keeps the vocabulary consistent.

\subsection{APOT Model Adaptation}
The original APOT model \cite{outay2024} follows a cyclic Assess, Predict, Oversee, and Transit process, managed by LSAA, SOLMA, SOLPA, and SOLTA. Fig.~\ref{fig:apot_model} shows the original cycle. In our adaptation, the \textit{Assess} stage becomes the MCQ Evaluator Agent (filling the SOLMA role) by monitoring whether the answer is correct. The \textit{Predict} stage becomes the Difficulty Predictor Agent (the SOLPA role) by classifying the question's difficulty. The \textit{Oversee} and \textit{Transit} stages both map to the Adaptive MCQ Overseer Agent (the SOLTA role), which synthesizes the earlier analyses and decides on transitions. The LSAA function shows up in the form of domain-aware question generation and multi-domain competency tracking---not a dedicated agent, since our question-only setting doesn't give us enough signal to detect learning style the way an AR system can.

