\subsection{Dual-Layer Difficulty Adaptation}
One key design choice is decoupling UI responsiveness from the heavier multi-agent pipeline. The \textbf{Synchronous Layer} kicks in the moment an answer is submitted, applying a deterministic rule-based mapping: if the answer is correct, Easy$\rightarrow$Medium, Medium$\rightarrow$Hard, Hard$\rightarrow$Hard; if it's wrong, Hard$\rightarrow$Medium, Medium$\rightarrow$Easy, Easy$\rightarrow$Easy. The next question is generated at this difficulty and sent back in the JSON response, so the UI updates in under a second. The \textbf{Asynchronous Layer} spawns a daemon thread that runs the full MCQ Evaluator Agent $\rightarrow$ Difficulty Predictor Agent $\rightarrow$ Adaptive MCQ Overseer Agent CrewAI pipeline. Its analysis is then persisted to \texttt{QuestionPerformance} and \texttt{AdaptiveLearningHistory}, and \texttt{final\_difficulty} is updated. The thread closes its DB connection in a \texttt{finally} block so we don't leak connections.

This split was a practical call. Early in development we tried running the CrewAI pipeline synchronously on the request thread, and the first few questions had 4--7 second waits between submission and the next question loading. That felt broken, so we moved the pipeline off the request path.

