\section{Multi-Agent Framework}
% -------------------------------------------------------

All agents run on Gemini 2.5 Flash through CrewAI's LLM interface (temperature 0.7), executing sequentially with context passed between tasks. We picked Gemini 2.5 Flash specifically because (i)~its latency is low enough that the asynchronous pipeline usually finishes before the student submits the next question, (ii)~it has a generous free-tier quota that made iterative development cheap, and (iii)~for short classification-style prompts like ours, we didn't see a quality gap compared to the larger Pro variant during informal testing.

\subsection{MCQ Evaluator Agent}
The MCQ Evaluator Agent plays the SOLMA (Stage of Learning Monitoring Agent) role, which corresponds to the APOT \textit{Assess} phase. Just as the original SOLMA keeps an eye on a learner's current performance \cite{outay2024}, this agent watches the quality of each immediate response. Its role is narrowly defined: act as a fair and accurate MCQ examiner. Given the question, the correct answer, the student's answer, and how long they took, it decides whether the answer is right and writes a one-line explanation. It's configured with \texttt{allow\_delegation=False} so that factual judgment stays separate from difficulty reasoning.

The agent's task takes in a structured input block containing:
\begin{itemize}
    \item The question text
    \item The correct answer
    \item The student's selected answer
    \item The time taken in seconds
\end{itemize}
Its output is a binary correctness verdict with a short justification, which serves as the factual foundation for the agents that come after it.

\subsection{Difficulty Predictor Agent}
The Difficulty Predictor Agent plays the SOLPA (Stage of Learning Prediction Agent) role, matching the APOT \textit{Predict} phase. It labels the current question as Easy, Medium, or Hard based on the MCQ Evaluator Agent's verdict and the student's response time. The backstory spells it out: ``Fast + Correct = Easy. Slow + Correct = Medium. Wrong = Hard.'' This reflects the long-standing idea that response time combined with correctness is a reasonable behavioral proxy for difficulty \cite{weiss2004}. There are no hard-coded thresholds---the LLM decides what counts as ``fast'' or ``slow'' in context. In practice we noticed the agent tends to treat anything under 15 seconds as fast and anything over 40 as slow, but that's emergent from the model rather than something we set.

\subsection{Adaptive MCQ Overseer Agent}
The Adaptive MCQ Overseer Agent plays the SOLTA (Stage of Learning Transition Agent) role, covering both the \textit{Oversee} and \textit{Transit} phases. Where the original SOLTA decides when and how a learner should move between competency stages \cite{outay2024}, this agent decides when and how to move between difficulty levels, which directly reflects how the student's competency is developing. It takes the MCQ Evaluator Agent and Difficulty Predictor Agent outputs as context and produces two things: (1) a confirmed current difficulty, and (2) a recommended next difficulty. Its backstory encodes adaptive rules grounded in the Zone of Proximal Development \cite{vygotsky1978} and Bloom's taxonomy \cite{bloom1956}:

\textbf{If the answer is correct:}
\begin{itemize}
    \item Easy $\rightarrow$ Next: Medium (increase challenge)
    \item Medium $\rightarrow$ Next: Hard (advance to next level)
    \item Hard $\rightarrow$ Next: Hard or Medium (maintain mastery)
\end{itemize}

\textbf{If the answer is incorrect:}
\begin{itemize}
    \item Hard $\rightarrow$ Next: Medium (step down one level)
    \item Medium $\rightarrow$ Next: Easy (step down one level)
    \item Easy $\rightarrow$ Next: Easy (stay at same level for confidence building)
\end{itemize}

With \texttt{allow\_delegation=True}, the agent can check back with the earlier agents if it needs clarification. Its output follows a structured natural language format that's parsed line-by-line via keyword matching, with ``Medium'' as the default if parsing fails:

\begin{verbatim}
Questions Difficulty: [Easy/Medium/Hard]
Next Question Difficulty: [Easy/Medium/Hard]
Reasoning: [explanation]
Recommendation: [additional actions]
\end{verbatim}

\subsection{CrewAI Orchestration}
The three agents are wired together into a \texttt{Crew} with \texttt{Process.sequential}, \texttt{memory=False}, and \texttt{max\_rpm=10}. Task 3 (Adaptive MCQ Overseer Agent) declares \texttt{context=[task1, task2]} so it can see the MCQ Evaluator Agent and Difficulty Predictor Agent outputs. Calling \texttt{crew.kickoff()} runs the pipeline and returns the Adaptive MCQ Overseer Agent's output. Fig.~\ref{fig:pipeline} shows the full pipeline.

