\section{Implementation Details}
\label{sec:implementation}
% -------------------------------------------------------

This section describes the concrete setup we used during development and deployment, along with representative code patterns from the actual implementation.

\subsection{Development and Deployment Environment}
The system was developed on a laptop running Ubuntu 22.04 LTS with an Intel Core i5 processor and 16~GB of RAM, and was also tested on Windows 11 to confirm portability. The server-side stack uses Python 3.11, Django 4.2.11, and MySQL 8.0.36 (accessed via \texttt{mysqlclient}). The CrewAI version is 0.28.x, and the Google Generative AI SDK (\texttt{google-generativeai}) is pinned to version 0.7.x for stability. Supporting packages include \texttt{python-dotenv} for configuration, \texttt{redis-py} for the optional Celery queue (not used in the default synchronous deployment), and \texttt{gunicorn} as the WSGI server when deployed behind Nginx. Development was done in VS Code; deployment was tested on a small DigitalOcean droplet (2 vCPU, 4~GB RAM) which turned out to be more than enough for single-user load.

\subsection{Representative Agent Configuration}
Listing~\ref{lst:agents} shows a simplified version of the CrewAI agent definitions. The actual code has more comments and guard logic but follows the same shape.

\begin{lstlisting}[language=Python,caption={Simplified CrewAI agent setup.},label={lst:agents}]
from crewai import Agent, Task, Crew, Process, LLM

llm = LLM(
    model="gemini/gemini-2.5-flash",
    temperature=0.7,
    api_key=GEMINI_API_KEY,
)

evaluator = Agent(
    role="MCQ Evaluator",
    goal="Decide whether the student's answer "
         "is correct and explain briefly.",
    backstory=(
        "You are a fair and accurate examiner. "
        "Compare the student's choice to the "
        "correct answer and return a clear "
        "verdict with a short justification."
    ),
    llm=llm,
    allow_delegation=False,
    verbose=False,
)

predictor = Agent(
    role="Difficulty Predictor",
    goal="Classify the question as Easy, "
         "Medium, or Hard.",
    backstory=(
        "Use this heuristic: "
        "Fast + Correct = Easy. "
        "Slow + Correct = Medium. "
        "Wrong = Hard. "
        "Read 'fast' and 'slow' in context."
    ),
    llm=llm,
    allow_delegation=False,
)

overseer = Agent(
    role="Adaptive MCQ Overseer",
    goal="Confirm current difficulty and "
         "recommend the next one.",
    backstory=OVERSEER_RULES,  # ZPD + Bloom rules
    llm=llm,
    allow_delegation=True,
)
\end{lstlisting}

\subsection{Task Wiring and Pipeline Kickoff}
The three tasks are linked so that the overseer can read both earlier outputs via CrewAI's \texttt{context} parameter. Listing~\ref{lst:tasks} captures the essential wiring.

\begin{lstlisting}[language=Python,caption={Task definitions and crew kickoff.},label={lst:tasks}]
task1 = Task(
    description=f"""
    Evaluate the following response:
    Question: {question_text}
    Correct Answer: {correct_answer}
    Student Selected Answer: {student_answer}
    Time Taken by Student: {time_taken} seconds
    Return: verdict (correct/incorrect)
    and a one-line justification.
    """,
    agent=evaluator,
    expected_output="Verdict + justification",
)

task2 = Task(
    description="Classify the question as "
                "Easy, Medium, or Hard based on "
                "correctness and time.",
    agent=predictor,
    expected_output="One of: Easy | Medium | Hard",
)

task3 = Task(
    description=OVERSEER_TASK_TEMPLATE,
    agent=overseer,
    context=[task1, task2],
    expected_output=(
        "Questions Difficulty, "
        "Next Question Difficulty, "
        "Reasoning, Recommendation."
    ),
)

crew = Crew(
    agents=[evaluator, predictor, overseer],
    tasks=[task1, task2, task3],
    process=Process.sequential,
    memory=False,
    max_rpm=10,
)

result = crew.kickoff()
\end{lstlisting}

\subsection{Question Generation Prompt}
Questions are generated on demand through a direct \texttt{google-generativeai} call rather than through a CrewAI agent, since generation is not part of the APOT reasoning loop. The prompt enforces a strict JSON schema so parsing is predictable. Listing~\ref{lst:genprompt} gives a trimmed version.

\begin{lstlisting}[caption={MCQ generation prompt (trimmed).},label={lst:genprompt}]
Generate exactly ONE multiple choice question
for the topic "{topic}" at "{difficulty}"
difficulty level.

Constraints:
- Four options labelled A, B, C, D
- Exactly one correct answer
- No duplicated or ambiguous options
- Avoid questions already asked in this
  session: {asked_questions_summary}

Return ONLY valid JSON with this schema:
{
  "question": "<text>",
  "options": {
    "A": "<text>", "B": "<text>",
    "C": "<text>", "D": "<text>"
  },
  "correct_answer": "A" | "B" | "C" | "D",
  "difficulty": "Easy" | "Medium" | "Hard",
  "topic": "<topic>"
}
Do not include markdown fences or commentary.
\end{lstlisting}

The generated text is then stripped of any accidental code fences (\texttt{```json} markers that Gemini occasionally adds despite instructions) before being passed to \texttt{json.loads}.

\subsection{Step-by-Step Data Flow for One Answer}
To make the runtime behavior concrete, here is what happens when a student clicks ``Submit'' on question $n$:

\begin{enumerate}
    \item The browser sends a POST request to \texttt{/submit\_answer/} with the selected option, the question index $n$, and the client-measured time in seconds.
    \item The Django view looks up the session by \texttt{assessment\_id}, validates that the test is still \texttt{in\_progress}, and checks the server-side timer.
    \item The selected answer is appended to the session's \texttt{answers} list, and timing info is stored.
    \item The synchronous rule-based fallback immediately computes the next difficulty based on correctness and current difficulty, so the UI doesn't have to wait for the LLM.
    \item A daemon \texttt{threading.Thread} is spawned to run the CrewAI pipeline with the question, correct answer, selected answer, and time. This thread does not block the HTTP response.
    \item The view calls the question generator for the next question at the fallback difficulty and returns it in the JSON response.
    \item The browser receives the JSON, updates the progress bar, swaps the question card, and resets the per-question timer.
    \item In the background, the CrewAI thread completes (usually within 2--4 seconds), writes \texttt{QuestionPerformance} and \texttt{AdaptiveLearningHistory} rows, updates \texttt{StudentTestResult.final\_difficulty}, and closes its DB connection inside a \texttt{finally} block.
\end{enumerate}

If the background thread is still running when question $n+1$ is submitted, that's fine---the two threads write to different rows. Race conditions are avoided because each question has its own \texttt{question\_number} key.

\subsection{Frontend Behavior}
The frontend is deliberately thin. It keeps a single client-side state object holding the current question, the per-question start timestamp, and a running list of answers. The 20-minute test timer is driven by \texttt{setInterval} on a 1-second tick, and the per-question timer uses \texttt{Date.now()} differences instead of a separate interval to avoid drift. A \texttt{beforeunload} handler fires a \texttt{navigator.sendBeacon} POST to \texttt{/auto\_submit/}, which marks the test as \texttt{auto\_submitted} server-side even if the browser is closing.

