\section{System Analysis and Discussion}
% -------------------------------------------------------

\subsection{Agent Role Separation and Pipeline Integrity}
The three-agent design enforces a clean separation of concerns that directly mirrors the APOT model's staged reasoning \cite{outay2024}. The MCQ Evaluator Agent only handles factual comparison, so correctness stays isolated from any difficulty-related reasoning. The Difficulty Predictor Agent only applies psychometric heuristics to the current question, without worrying about adaptation goals. And the Adaptive MCQ Overseer Agent is the one piece that pulls correctness, difficulty prediction, and adaptive rules together to produce actionable transition recommendations that reflect where the student is headed. This staged design keeps concerns from getting tangled up and makes each agent's reasoning independently auditable. Table~\ref{tab:agent_roles} summarizes the mapping.

