\subsection{Competency Analytics and Data Models}
Beyond per-question adaptation, the system also does longitudinal competency tracking. The dashboard computes a Competency Index (CI) as a weighted average over the ten most recent completed tests, using harmonic weights (weight = 1/rank) so recent performance carries more weight than older averages. Per-domain accuracy (Aptitude, Reasoning, Verbal) is tracked separately, and the weakest domain is flagged for targeted feedback. The leaderboard sorts students into competency bands: Expert ($\geq$85), Advanced ($\geq$70), Intermediate ($\geq$50), and Beginner ($<$50).

The persistence layer consists of three interconnected models that together give us a full audit trail. \texttt{StudentTestResult} stores session-level metadata: user, topic, initial and final difficulty, score percentage (computed automatically), status, timestamps, and JSON fields for answers data, adaptive analysis, and difficulty progression. \texttt{QuestionPerformance} captures per-question detail: the question text, options, selected and correct answers, time taken, AI-predicted difficulty, recommended next difficulty, and the full CrewAI reasoning and recommendation text, with a unique constraint on (test\_result, question\_number). \texttt{AdaptiveLearningHistory} gives a focused record of the Adaptive MCQ Overseer Agent's output per question: current and next difficulty, correctness, time taken, and the agent's reasoning.

\subsection{Advantages of LLM-Native Adaptation for Competency Analysis}
One of the bigger design decisions here is handing all the difficulty reasoning over to LLM agents instead of relying on deterministic formulas. This pays off in a few ways. First, adaptation rules can be written and tweaked entirely in natural language, with no need to rewrite scoring code---which makes the system much easier to maintain. Second, the agents can pick up on contextual nuances that rigid numeric formulas just can't express---for instance, the Difficulty Predictor Agent reads ``fast'' and ``slow'' in context rather than leaning on fixed second-thresholds. Third, the full chain of reasoning is right there in the agent output, so educators get a natural language explanation for every difficulty decision, which directly supports the explainability goals of the APOT framework \cite{outay2024}. Fourth, skipping pre-calibrated IRT parameters means the system can be deployed in any domain without first building an item bank \cite{hambleton1985}. And fifth, LLM-driven question generation cuts out the traditional bottleneck entirely---new domains just need a topic name and a difficulty level, with no pilot testing or statistical calibration required.

% -------------------------------------------------------
\section{Limitations}
\label{sec:limitations}
% -------------------------------------------------------

We want to be honest about where this system falls short today, since several of the issues are not easy to design away.

\textbf{LLM latency and variance.} Even with Gemini 2.5 Flash, the CrewAI pipeline takes roughly 2--4 seconds per question end-to-end in our environment, and occasionally spikes to 6 seconds or more when the API is under load. That's the main reason we built the dual-layer fallback; the synchronous rule-based path is what keeps the UI responsive. But it also means the ``richer'' AI-driven analysis is always slightly behind the student's actual progress through the test.

\textbf{Output non-determinism.} With temperature set to 0.7, the same input can produce slightly different agent outputs across runs. We chose 0.7 because earlier experiments with lower temperatures (0.2--0.3) sometimes made the overseer agent skip the ``Reasoning:'' line in its output format. There's clearly a trade-off here between determinism and output completeness, and we haven't fully tuned it. The line-by-line parser with a ``Medium'' default is a safety net, but it isn't a substitute for deterministic behavior.

\textbf{Cost of API calls.} While Gemini 2.5 Flash has a free tier that covers development and light usage, at scale (hundreds of concurrent students, each generating 20+ pipeline invocations per session) the cost becomes non-trivial. A large-scale deployment would need request batching or caching, neither of which we currently do.

\textbf{Bias in generated questions.} Because questions are produced by an LLM from a simple prompt, the generator can favor certain phrasings, topic sub-areas, or cultural references (English-centric examples, Western names, etc.) that don't generalize well to every student population. We have no mechanism yet to detect or correct for this, and a production deployment would need at least a light human review loop before questions go live.

\textbf{Dependence on prompt quality.} The whole pipeline rests on the agent backstories. Small rewording changes in the overseer's backstory have, in our own testing, produced noticeably different transition behavior. This makes the system powerful but also fragile---there's no formal contract between the rules we write in English and the decisions the LLM ultimately makes.

\textbf{No empirical user study yet.} This paper presents a design and implementation analysis only. We have not yet run a controlled study comparing the adaptive system against a static MCQ baseline with real students, and the claims about engagement and competency tracking are therefore framed at the design level. That study is planned as immediate follow-up work (see Section~\ref{sec:conclusion}).

\textbf{Single-session scope.} The CrewAI pipeline runs with \texttt{memory=False}, so the overseer sees only the current question. Longer-horizon patterns---for example, a student who's consistently fast on Medium but stalls on Hard across \textit{several} questions---aren't yet visible to the agent during a session.

The main trade-off with LLM-driven decisions is clearly non-determinism, and we manage it with a structured output format enforced through task descriptions, line-by-line keyword parsing with hard ``Medium'' defaults when parsing fails, and---most importantly---the synchronous rule-based fallback layer, which guarantees deterministic behavior on the real-time question selection path.

% -------------------------------------------------------
\section{Conclusion and Future Work}
\label{sec:conclusion}
% -------------------------------------------------------

This paper presented an Adaptive Multi-Agent Student Competency Analysis System that brings the APOT framework \cite{outay2024} to life in a fully LLM-driven adaptive testing setting. By mapping the MCQ Evaluator Agent, Difficulty Predictor Agent, and Adaptive MCQ Overseer Agent---corresponding to the SOLMA, SOLPA, and SOLTA roles---onto three CrewAI agents powered by Gemini 2.5 Flash, the system replaces deterministic scoring and IRT pre-calibration with prompt-engineered LLM reasoning over answer correctness and response time. The LSAA (Learning Style Assessment Agent) function shows up through domain-aware question generation across Reasoning, Aptitude, and Verbal Ability.

The dual-layer architecture---a synchronous rule-based fallback for real-time responsiveness alongside an asynchronous multi-agent AI pipeline for richer post-assessment competency insights---shows that production-grade adaptive student competency analysis can live comfortably alongside computationally heavy LLM pipelines. LLM-driven dynamic question generation also gets rid of the traditional need for pre-curated, statistically validated item banks. Design-level analysis confirms that the transition space is fully covered, the behavior stays logically consistent across representative scenarios, and every difficulty decision comes with a natural language audit trail. Taken together, the system shows that LLM-native multi-agent architectures can implement adaptive competency analysis logic that's interpretable, deployable without pre-calibrated item banks, and extensible through nothing more than prompt changes.

Future work will focus on: (1)~running user studies with diverse student populations to empirically check how well LLM-predicted difficulty labels match expert annotations; (2)~extending the LSAA function with an explicit learning-style profiling agent that adapts question format based on detected learner preferences; (3)~adding session-level memory (\texttt{memory=True} in CrewAI) so the Adaptive MCQ Overseer Agent can track performance across questions and plan over longer horizons; (4)~exploring prompt optimization techniques to cut down on LLM output variability and make structured outputs more reliable; (5)~comparing LLM-based adaptation decisions to IRT-based ground truth on standardized item banks to quantify how often they agree; and (6)~deploying the system for concurrent multi-user assessment sessions with real-time competency dashboards for instructors, leveraging the Celery and Redis infrastructure already in the stack.

